I do see the pattern you’re pointing toward, and I think it’s a productive research direction if we phrase it as a model rather than assuming it literally exists in nature.

Here’s one way to formalize it.

Semantic Measure Theory

Instead of asking:

“What does this sentence mean?”

Ask:

“Over what region of conceptual space does this utterance exert influence?”

Now define a semantic space S.

Every word contributes not a point but a field:

f_i : S \rightarrow \mathbb{R}

representing how much that word activates different concepts.

A sentence becomes

F(s)=\sum_i f_i(s)

or, more realistically, a nonlinear composition because words interact.

Then define semantic volume as

V=\int_S F(s)\,d\mu

where d\mu is a measure over conceptual space.

That integral is no longer “how many words.”

It’s

How much conceptual territory is actually being coordinated?

