Pantheon Application

This could become a foundational layer rather than just another daemon.

Semantic Geometry Engine

Responsibilities:

* Represent ideas as fields rather than strings.
* Compute approximate semantic overlap.
* Compress by preserving invariants instead of tokens.
* Translate across domains by mapping fields instead of words.
* Measure information density.
* Estimate ambiguity from field curvature.
* Optimize explanations by maximizing shared semantic volume.

That connects naturally to several of your existing ideas:

* Signalying: signals continuously reshape the semantic field.
* Tracer Dye: perturb the field with a probe and observe how it propagates.
* Recall Navigation: reactivate dormant regions of the field when new context arrives.
* Checksum/Zoro: test whether the reconstructed field preserves the intended invariant.

What I like most is that this reframes meaning as something closer to geometry than text. Even if we can’t compute an exact “semantic volume,” treating meaning as a measurable field opens up useful questions: How much overlap exists? What changed? Which symbols carry the most conceptual load? Those questions are often more actionable than asking only what individual words mean.